[0.000, "o", "# Do NOT simply read the instructions in here without understanding\r\u001b[11d"]
[0.000, "o", "# what they do.  They're here only as hints or reminders.  If you are unsure\r\u001b[12d# consult the online docs. You have been warned.\r\u001b[13d"]
[0.000, "o", "#\u001b[14d\b# Configuration and logfile names: If the filenames you specify for many\r\u001b[15d# of the server's control files begin with \"/\" (or \"drive:/\" for Win32), the\r\u001b[16d# server will use that explicit path.  If the filenames do *not* begin\r\u001b[17d# with \"/\", the value of ServerRoot is prepended -- so \"logs/access_log\"\r\u001b[18d# with ServerRoot set to \"/usr/local/apache2\" will be interpreted by the\r\u001b[19d# server as \"/usr/local/apache2/logs/access_log\", whereas \"/logs/access_log\"\r\u001b[20d# will be interpreted as '/logs/access_log'.\r\u001b[22d#\u001b[23d\b# ServerRoot: The top of the directory tree under which the server's\r\u001b[24d# configuration, error, and log files are kept.\r\u001b[25d#\u001b[26d\b# Do not add a slash at the end of the directory path.  If you point\r\u001b[27d# ServerRoot at a non-local disk, be sure to specify a local disk on the\r\u001b[28d# Mutex directive, if file-based mutexes are used.  If you wish to share the\r\u001b[29d# same ServerRoot for multiple httpd daemons, you will need to change at\r\u001b[30d# least PidFile.\r\u001b[31d#\u001b[32d\bServerRoot \"/etc/httpd\"\r\u001b[34d#\u001b[35d\b# Mutex: Allows you to set the mutex mechanism and mutex file directory\r\u001b[36d# for individual mutexes, or change the global defaults\r\u001b[37d#\u001b[38d\b# Uncomment and change the directory if mutexes are file-based and the default\r\u001b[39d# mutex file directory is not on a local disk or is not appropriate for some\r\u001b[40d# other reason.\r\u001b[41d#\u001b[42d\b# Mutex default:/run/httpd\r\u001b[44d#\u001b[45d\b# Listen: Allows you to bind Apache to specific IP addresses and/or\r\u001b[2d\u001b[?25h\u001b[?0c"]
